{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:55:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:55:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15440"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15440"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.16,0.49,0.11,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102436"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3073"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48256"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102436"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of disturbed sleep, irritability, and difficulty concentrating at work. She works as a police officer and recently spent six months investigating child abuse cases, reviewing video evidence and interviewing victims. She has become increasingly withdrawn, avoiding social activities and experiencing intrusive thoughts about the cases. She has no history of direct physical trauma or injury. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious with vital signs within normal limits. She becomes tearful when discussing work but has no thoughts of self-harm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute stress disorder","Burnout syndrome","Post-traumatic stress disorder","Adjustment disorder","Major depressive disorder"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a diagnostic challenge in PTSD as it involves indirect trauma exposure through repeated exposure to aversive details of traumatic events, rather than direct experience or witnessing of trauma. The DSM-5 specifically includes this type of exposure as qualifying for PTSD diagnosis, particularly in first responders and investigators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-traumatic stress disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnosis. The patient demonstrates key symptoms including intrusive thoughts, avoidance behaviour, negative changes in mood (social withdrawal), and altered arousal/reactivity (irritability, sleep disturbance, concentration problems); all of these domains must be fulfilled through various criteria for the diagnosis of PTSD. The symptoms have persisted for more than one month, are causing functional impairment, and are not attributable to another medical condition nor physiological effects of a substance, all of which must be demonstrated for this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered, but this diagnosis is typically used when symptoms develop in response to an identifiable stressor that does not meet criteria for trauma exposure. The severity and specific symptom pattern here better align with PTSD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E shares some symptoms with PTSD, including sleep disturbance and concentration problems. However, the presence of intrusive thoughts specifically related to work trauma exposure and avoidance behaviour makes PTSD more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute stress disorder\u003C/strong\u003E presents similarly to PTSD but is diagnosed only in the first month following trauma exposure. This patient\u0027s symptoms have persisted for three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBurnout syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by emotional exhaustion, depersonalisation, and reduced personal accomplishment due to chronic workplace stress. While relevant to first responders, it does not typically include the specific trauma-related symptoms seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe case highlights the importance of recognising that PTSD can develop from indirect trauma exposure in occupational settings, particularly among first responders and investigators who are repeatedly exposed to details of traumatic events.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["PTSD diagnosis requires exposure to actual or threatened death, serious injury, or violence, either directly or by witnessing it happening to others.","Symptoms must persist for more than one month and cause significant functional impairment.","Repeated exposure to aversive details of traumatic events (e.g., first responders) can qualify as trauma exposure for PTSD diagnosis."],"references":["Soravia LM, Schwab S, Walther S, M\u00fcller T. Rescuers at Risk: Posttraumatic Stress Symptoms Among Police Officers, Fire Fighters, Ambulance Personnel, and Emergency and Psychiatric Nurses. Frontiers in Psychiatry. 2021 Jan 19;11.\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T18:36:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T18:38:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102436"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"h